	   <tr><td colspan=2>Osano is dead-on here.&nbsp;&nbsp;I love playing my monk, but a monk is definitely not the way to go if you want to be a soloer.  You are also in the toughest level range for monks - I remember feeling way under-powered in my mid to high teens, and got kinda frustrated.  On the other hand, I started appreciating the unique abilities of monks once I got into the low to mid 20s, really started feeling strong in the 30s, and at lvl 42 my combat skills are better than my friend's lvl 54 warrior.  I laugh every time the tanks complain that the scroll window is so spammed full of "Keyeluke crushes ...." that they can't see their own hits happening.  Four-hits and five-hits are damn impressive, and throwing flying kicks for 97 points of damage makes people take notice.  Travelling is a piece of cake.  The run from FV to Overthere is a perfect example - my brother was scared to death of running his lvl 35 ranger through Frontier Mountains - even with SoW - while I didnt even give it a thought at a much lower level.  Something aggro's you - run a bit to take it from its spawn point, feign out - if you fail first feign, just wait, time it better, and feign again.  You just resume your trip a minute later, no harm no foul.  And I too have tested many mobs - tried to kill the griffin in EC a few levels ago.  Conned blue to me, but it took me down to 2 bubbles and it was still 2/3, so I ran a bit, feigned, and got back to my regular business.<br><br>The monk is a critical member of melee groups, and pretty much required for feign-pulling in nastier zones.  Monks dish damage like no one else, monks have all sorts of special skills that make playing the class so much more interesting than just straight tanking, and I am very satisfied that I chose to play a monk.<br><br>Any class you play calls for you to play within the parameters of that class.  If you want to be a soloer, you'll need to consider a caster or hybrid class.  I don't believe the pure melee classes are good choices for soloing.  Monks should be able to solo better than warriors because monks can bring themselves to full health with bind wound and mend in 7-8 minutes or so, and monks can get out of trouble with little angst.  But I don't feel monks are for soloing.  Monks are important components of good groups.  No one pulls better than a monk - just like no one heals better than a cleric, no one buffs better than a shaman, no one soaks up damage better than a warrior, etc etc.  A group can still work with alternate classes performing these functions, but not nearly as well.<br><br>Monks are very interesting to play.  There is a lot to do during every melee - as a puller you'll have less time to chat and do nothing than any other class.  Managing weight becomes a prime consideration, and a very interesting challenge, and affects many of your decisions during the game.  You'll find yourself spending a LOT of time practicing your skills - but they are well worth it.  I have instill doubt up to 198, and have grouped with a ranger to fear-kite all sorts of mobs with great success.  I can run through mountainous zones without blinking - everyone else eats damage on every steep downhill.  I have little fear running through spooky zones.<br><br>I urge you to stick with your monk.  You're in the toughest level range for the class - a few more levels and you'll appreciate all the great things about being a monk.  On the other hand, if you want to be a soloer, the way of the monk is not really for you.<br><br>Keyeluke<br>Monk of the Silent Fist, 42nd Circle<br>Strange Brew<br>Druzzil Ro<br>&nbsp;<br>Keyeluke<br>Member of Tenacity - Druzzil Ro<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=27415" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=27415</a></td></tr>
